        body: 'High availability (HA) is the broader design goal that cold/warm/hot DR sites serve one large-scale version of: keeping a system reachable and functioning through the failure of any single component, without waiting for a full-blown disaster. The core technique underneath nearly every HA design is redundancy — deploying more than one instance of a critical component so a single failure doesn\'t take the whole system down — paired with failover, the mechanism that actually detects a failure and shifts traffic or workload onto the surviving redundant component. That pattern shows up throughout networking at every layer: a First Hop Redundancy Protocol like HSRP or VRRP keeps a default gateway reachable if one router fails, link aggregation keeps a connection up if one physical link in a bundle fails, and Spanning Tree keeps a redundant switch topology loop-free while still holding backup paths in reserve. HA deployments are commonly described as active-active, where every redundant component handles live traffic simultaneously and only some capacity is lost if one fails, or active-passive, where a standby component sits idle until a failure promotes it into service — a distinction that maps directly onto the active/standby roles a protocol like HSRP already uses for its own gateway redundancy.',
