        title: 'DHCP: Lease Process, Relay & SLAAC',
        body: 'DHCP (RFC 2131) assigns an IPv4 address to a joining host through a four-message exchange commonly abbreviated DORA: the client broadcasts a DHCPDISCOVER looking for any server, servers reply with a DHCPOFFER proposing an address, the client broadcasts a DHCPREQUEST accepting one specific offer so any other servers know theirs wasn\'t taken, and the chosen server confirms with a DHCPACK. Because a DHCPDISCOVER is only a local broadcast, a DHCP server living on a different subnet from the client needs a BOOTP/DHCP relay agent — commonly a router configured with an "ip helper"-style command — to forward the broadcast on as a unicast, stamping in the relay agent\'s own address so the server knows which subnet to allocate an address from. Every lease also carries two renewal timers: T1, defaulting to 50% of the lease duration, is when the client starts trying to renew with its original server, and T2, defaulting to 87.5% of the lease, is when it broadens that attempt to any server in case the original one is unreachable. IPv6 offers a path that skips DHCP entirely: SLAAC (Stateless Address Autoconfiguration, RFC 4862) lets a host generate its own global address from the network prefix a router advertises, verifying the result is actually unique on the link through Duplicate Address Detection before using it — a stateless approach that DHCPv6 can still complement when an administrator needs to hand out settings, like DNS servers, that SLAAC alone doesn\'t cover.',
