        title: 'DNS Record Types & Zone Types',
        body: "A DNS zone is the administrative unit a name server is authoritative for — the actual data for a domain, held in a master file (RFC 1035) on a primary server, with one or more secondary servers periodically pulling updates from that primary through a zone transfer to stay in sync as an authoritative backup. Within a zone, different resource record types answer different kinds of questions: an A record maps a hostname to an IPv4 address, with AAAA doing the same job for IPv6 once that record type was added as DNS grew to support the newer address family; a CNAME record is an alias pointing one hostname at another's canonical name; an MX record identifies which server handles mail for a domain; a TXT record holds arbitrary descriptive text, commonly used today for domain-ownership verification and email-security policies; and a PTR record does the reverse of an A record, mapping an IP address back to a hostname. Every zone also has exactly one SOA (Start of Authority) record, which RFC 1035 defines as marking the start of a zone of authority and carrying the zone's own administrative parameters, like the refresh interval secondary servers use when checking the primary for updates. Zones also split along a second axis, forward zones (name-to-address) versus reverse zones (address-to-name, built from PTR records), which is why a fully documented DNS deployment maintains both directions rather than just the forward lookups end users actually type into a browser.",
