        title: 'DNSSEC (RFC 4033)',
        body: "Plain DNS has no way to prove that a response actually came from a zone's real authoritative source and wasn't tampered with in transit — a gap that made cache-poisoning and off-path spoofing attacks possible for decades. DNSSEC (DNS Security Extensions), introduced in RFC 4033, closes that gap by adding data origin authentication and data integrity to DNS responses, without touching DNS's basic query-and-response mechanics or attempting to provide confidentiality — a DNSSEC-signed answer is still sent in the clear, just cryptographically verifiable. It works by having each zone sign its own records with a private key, publishing the corresponding public key in a DNSKEY record, and chaining trust upward: a resolver that already trusts a parent zone's key can verify a DS (Delegation Signer) record pointing to the child zone's key, and follow that chain link by link up to a trust anchor it was configured with directly, rather than trusting every layer blindly. A resolver performing this validation is described as security-aware; one that isn't simply ignores the extra signature records and behaves exactly like classic DNS. Because DNSSEC only adds authentication and integrity, it does nothing to encrypt the contents of a DNS query itself — that gap in DNS privacy is what DoH and DoT, covered next, were built to close instead.",
