        body: "Accurate, synchronized clocks matter more in networking than they might seem — log timestamps only let an analyst correlate events across devices if every device's clock agrees, and some authentication protocols and certificate validations fail outright if a device's clock drifts too far from reality. NTP (Network Time Protocol, RFC 5905) is the standard mechanism for this over ordinary IP networks: clients synchronize against a hierarchy of time servers, and NTPv4's mitigation and discipline algorithms can hold accuracy to the tens of microseconds on a modern workstation over a fast LAN — more than precise enough for log correlation, authentication windows, and everyday scheduling. Some applications need tighter precision than that: industrial control systems, financial trading platforms, and telecom infrastructure often require sub-microsecond synchronization across an entire network, which is what PTP (Precision Time Protocol, IEEE 1588) is built for. IEEE 1588 itself is a paywalled standard with no free canonical text, but per a Cisco configuration guide describing a practical PTP deployment, the protocol elects a grandmaster clock through a Best Master Clock Algorithm that continuously reassesses which clock on the network is the best available reference, and a well-configured PTP network can hold slave devices synchronized to within about 1 microsecond of the grandmaster even 16 hops away — an order of magnitude tighter than NTP's typical accuracy, at the cost of needing PTP-aware switches and hardware throughout the path rather than running over any ordinary IP network the way NTP does.",
